definitions.example: I had hoped our first meeting would turn out better.

definitions.definition: (by ellipsis) To succeed; work out; turn out well.
definitions.example: I'm afraid the cake didn't turn out.
Hundreds of people turned out to see the parade.

definitions.definition: To extinguish a light or other device
definitions.example: Turn out the lights before you leave.

definitions.definition: To become apparent or known, especially (as) it turns out
definitions.example: It turns out that he just made a lucky guess.
The bakery turns out three hundred pies each day.
Turn out at the third driveway.

definitions.definition: To remove from a mould, bowl etc.
definitions.example: Turn out the dough onto a board and shape it.

definitions.definition: To refuse service or shelter; to eject or evict.
definitions.example: The hotel staff hastened to turn out the noisy drunk.

definitions.definition: (sex) To convince a person (usually a woman) to become a prostitute.
(sex) To rape; to coerce an otherwise heterosexual individual into performing a homosexual role.
To leave one's work to take part in a strike.
To get out of bed; get up.
